The Welkin's Flow DataTable is a universal component that is able to display any records, however it could not accept Record Collection variables.

To display records in the component - you need to pass a Text Collection with their IDs.


This is why there is a separate loop in the flow to convert Record Collection to a Text Collection.

As you can see below - the DataTable component provides a lot of controls for your users:

  • They can sort using any column
  • They can search through the list of records
  • They have handy pagination options
  • etc.
The easiest way to start working with the Welkin's Flow DataTable is to create a new Flow using the bundled template.

The Welkin's Flow DataTable components allows you to specify some input parameters:

  • Collection to be shown
  • Comma-separated list of fields to be shown (you can even reference parent fields)
  • Maximal number of records that a user can select in the list
  • Minimal number of records that a user should select in the list before proceeding
  • Collection of pre-selected records
  • An option to show the component's embedded navigation footer (described later)

Welkin's DataTable for Flows also provides admins and developers a way to force users to select a certain amount of records. You can even disable the "Next" or "Proceed" buttons until a users selects the minimal number of records.


To provide such a validation capability - the component has it's own embedded Navigation footer, and it is shown, that replicates standard footer, but adds such a validation.


You can enforce users to select a minimal number of records doing the following steps:

  1. Specify a minimal number of records to be selected in the options section for the component.
  2. Disable the standard Screen Footer on the particular screen.
  3. Place the DataTable component at the bottom of the screen.
  4. Set the "Enable custom footer" to True.

It is important to mention that the built-in navigation footer competely replicates the standard one, and it also get all it's settings - you don't need to configure any
